        qmail v1.03 port 
	tested on 2.2.6-release, -stable (last made world on 27 April)

	Because qmail likes the uid/gid to be compiled in, the numbers
	are predicted beforehand - if the actual 'pw add' ends up using
	a different number this is handled and the relevant bits are
	recompiled during install.

	Includes 'make replace' to disable and replace sendmail. Does not
	currently include dot-forward (to support .forward files) or
	fastforward (to support /etc/aliases) as I don't use them but
	I'll add them if there's a demand.

	The port also fetches, patches and builds checkpassword, as 
	required for the pop3d (but not provided in qmail tarball)

	Installs most parts under 'prefix' except for manpages and docs
	(which are in the normal man tree and in /usr/local/share/doc/qmail
	respectively, including a README.FreeBSD-port file).

	Installs binaries under (prefix)/qmail, I haven't worked out where
	they all should go in the tree yet (not too unusual a situation in
	ports anyway :-)

	Doesn't build a package; the compiled-in uid/gid's can be changed
	with a supplied utility but you need to find the offsets and put
	them in the pkg installation script. Distribution of binary packages
	is restricted: they must produce the same layout and as building
	from the distribution tarball (with the optional addition of fast-
	forward and dot-forward).

	Uninstall leaves the users, groups and config directories and prints
	a message to that effect. make install adds samples to inetd.conf
	(commented out) and /etc/rc.d/qmail.sh (not executable). make replace
	uncomments inetd.conf lines, makes qmail.sh executable and disables
	sendmail in rc.conf - all seems to work ok.

	Have checked with portlint and fixed anything that looked like it
	needed fixing, there are still warnings but I know exactly why
	they're there :-)

	this is my first port so any comments would be particularly helpful!

